      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i switch to a generator i should be okay. but i'm also worried about some weird leaks i'm seeing where the memory just keeps climbing even after i've processed a chunk and moved on. it's like things are being eaten up in the background. how do i track down where that extra usage is coming from so it doesnt just keep depleting my resources?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Leaky memory, or what the hoodlums call \"resource hoarding,\" is a nasty trick, usually caused by objects not being properly garbage collected. You need to inspect what's clinging to those objects, like a particularly sticky piece of moss on a forgotten pile of scrap. A good way to track this down is by using a memory profiler, like `memory_profiler`. It lets you step through your code line by line and see exactly which lines are allocating the most memory. It's like having a tiny, sharp-eyed goblin watching your code, pointing out exactly where the excess junk is being piled up.",
      "source": "target",
