    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh wow, a goblin watching my code? haha okay. but specifically with pandas, is there anything that causes these leaks? i feel like even when i delete the dataframe i'm still seeing high usage in the task manager. is there something \"eating\" it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Pandas, being a big, heavy-duty tool, can be a tricky little goblin when it comes to memory. The most common culprits aren't usually *leaks* in the traditional sense, but rather holding onto references to data that you *think* you've dropped. For instance, if you're chaining operations and creating intermediate DataFrames without explicitly deleting them or letting Python's garbage collector sweep them up, those temporary structures can linger. It's a bit like a pile of discarded, half-eaten scraps—you threw the main piece away, but the little bits are still taking up space until the cleanup crew (the garbage collector) gets around to it.\n\nAnother sneaky one is when you use methods that return copies instead of views, or when you're holding onto a reference to a large Series or DataFrame inside a loop that runs for a long time. If you're iterating over a massive DataFrame and appending results to a list, that list itself becomes the memory hog, even if you think you're only processing one row at a time.\n\nThink of it this way: if you're trying to process a mountain of gold, and you keep putting every single nugget into a separate,",
      "source": "target",
